
***************************************************************************
                              Making Armours
***************************************************************************
Note: All literal code in this help document is separated by a bunch of =
signs. The = signs are NOT part of the code. For example:

====================
#include <mudlib.h>
#include <types.h>
#include <material.h>
====================

refers to the three include lines, literally.


***************************************************************************
                              Basic Armours
***************************************************************************
A basic acceptable armour inherits GEN_ARMOUR and sets a few parameters.
Your armour file MUST have the following lines of code at the top:

====================
#include <mudlib.h>
#include <types.h>
#include <material.h>
#include <basic_armour.h>
inherit GEN_ARMOUR;
====================

If you want to put in comments before these lines, that's fine, but
these MUST precede any active code in the file.

Your armour MUST haved a reset function, with appropriate checks for
clones. That is, it must have the code:

====================
void reset(int iArg) {
    if (!is_clone(this_object())) return;
    ::reset(iArg);
    if (iArg) return;
====================

Even a basic armour has to have a few settings to make it interesting.
You should have the following settings for your armour:

For a standard armour form, prefer the shared template contract:

====================
set_armour_template("chainmail");
====================

Templates supply a canonical size, composition, coverage, default material,
aliases, weight, value, and material/quality-aware description. The clonable
stock forms live under /objects/standard_equipment/armour/. Call template
selection before deliberate overrides such as set_material(), set_quality(),
set_short(), or set_long(). Use query_armour_templates() to inspect the live
template names and query_armour_template_definition(name) to inspect one.

Area armour with custom prose can instead include <basic_armour.h> and use the
closest semantic ARMOUR_* identity:

====================
set_new_type(ARMOUR_BREASTPLATE);
====================

Do not assemble a recurring standard form from raw size, composition, and
coverage bits. Extend <basic_armour.h> when a genuinely recurring form is
missing. The individual setters below remain valid for exceptional forms and
for overriding template defaults.

set_short("short");
        Replace "short" with the quoted short description of your armour.
        The short description is the one a player sees when an object
        is just lying on the ground, in a shop, in someone's inventory etc.

set_long("long.\n");
        Replace "long" with the quoted long description of your armour.
        The long description is the one a player sees when he actually
        does a 'look' or 'examine' on an object. Remember to add both a
        period and a newline (\n) at the end of your description since
        LPC won't do that for you.

set_name("name");
        Replace "name" with the quoted name of your armour. This name
        should be the main name by which your armour is called, since it
        may show up on occasion in spam to players. It should never be
        a secret id key used to uniquely identify it for coding purposes.
        For example, "bobs_magic_plate_key" is a terrible name for an
        armour. It is often a good idea to use the short description of
        the armour as its name as well, but always use all lowercase
        letters and no articles. (e.g. "silver platemail" is good, but
        "a silver platemail" or "Silver Platemail" are bad).

set_alias("alias");
        Replace "alias" with the quoted alias of your armour. This alias
        can be any other way to refer to an armour. For example, if you
        had a silver platemail with the name "silver platemail" you would
        also want to have the aliases "silver plate", "platemail" and
        "mail" as aliases. If you want to use a secret id key to uniquely
        identify your armour, you can use set it as an alias. You can add
        multiple aliases by using this setting over and over again. This
        setting is optional.

set_new_type(TYPE1|TYPE2|etc.);
        Replace TYPE1|TYPE2|etc. with an ORed set of armour type values.
        That is, something that looks like:  MEDIUM|HIDE|TORSO
        Exactly one of the values must be a size (SMALL, MEDIUM, LARGE,
        or HUGE) and exactly one of the values must be an armor type
        (e.g. CLOTHES, PADDED, SCALE, CHAINMAIL etc.) Finally, at least
        one value must be a location (LEGS, TORSO, RING, SHOULDERS,
        AURA etc). RING and AMULET each allow two worn items. Other
        locations normally allow one worn item.

set_material(TYPE1|TYPE2|etc.);
        Replace TYPE1|TYPE2|etc. with an ORed set of material values.
        That is, something that looks like:  MAT_STEEL|MAT_WOOD
        Valid material types are listed in the material documentation,
        wizhelp 4.16 'materials'.

set_quality(quality);
        Replace quality with an integer quality value from -100 to 100.
        Quality is how good your armour is, compared to other armours
        of the given composition. A quality of 0 is average, and a quality
        of 100 is the best of the best. A -100 quality would be something
        laughably bad (like old, broken down rusty platemail that impedes
        more than it protects.) Any armour with a quality of greater than
        40 is considered at least exceptional. Any with a quality greater
        than 60 is unique. (see also wizhelp 4.14 'uniques'). Typical
        factors that should affect quality are: craftsmanship, wear/damage,
        rust, poor fit, odd shape, balance, extra thick/thin etc.

set_weight(weight);
        Replace weight with an integer weight value. This is the weight
        of the object. Weight on Darkwind also represents bulk and
        awkwardness of carrying.
        |CKBIf you want to have the game set a standard weight, you can
        set_weight(query_equipment_weight()); You need to use that after
        you have set_new_type() and set_material().|000

set_warmth(warmth);
        Replace warmth with an integer warmth value. This is how warm the
        piece is when worn. Warmth is used in rooms that use the inherit
        ARCTIC instead of room.
        |CKBOnly set this to override the default warmth.|XX0

set_value(-1);
        Armour values are automatically determined by the characteristics
        of the armour. Do not set a value for basic armours. (The -1
        means to use the automatically generated value). NB this should
        be the LAST function called in your reset routine.

That's it! An example manually configured armour is given in
/open/EXAMPLES/ARMOURS/basic_armour.c. Stock template examples are under
/objects/standard_equipment/armour/.

If all you want is to make a basic armour, copy that file to directory
where your area's armours are, and replace all the content values (e.g.
the quoted text used for set_long(), set_short() etc.) with your own
stuff.


***************************************************************************
                              Extra Settings
***************************************************************************
The following extra settings can be used in your armour as well, but are
not required:

set_read("text.\n");
        Replace "text.\n" with the quoted string to be seen when the
        armour is read. It there is writing on a helmet or ring, for
        example, you may wish to use this. Remember to add both a period
        and a newline (\n) at the end of your description since LPC won't
        do that for you.

set_info("info.\n");
        Replace "info.\n" with the quoted string to be seen when a mage
        or such identifies the armour. It should NEVER give specific
        numbers but it should give enough information for a person to get
        a fair idea of a armours strengths or powers.

set_no_buy();
        Put this in if this armour cannot be bought from the shop. (After
        someone has sold it as loot.)

set_no_sell(sell_setting);
        Replace sell_setting with an integer. If sell_setting is 1, the
        item will be marked as unsellable. If it is 0, it will clear
        a previously set sell_setting of 1. If you use a sell_setting
        greater than 1, then it will take that many calls of
        set_sell(0); to make it sellable again.

set_steal(1 or 0);
        If set_steal(1); is used, the armour is not stealable. If you
        set_steal(0); the armour will be stealable by thieves. Yes, it
        seems backwards and very stupid, which it is, but it is correct.

set_cursed(curse_chance);
        Replace curse_chance by an integer percentage indicating the
        likelihood of any clone of this armour being cursed. If this line
        is not used, objects will default to a 1% chance of being cursed.

set_no_curse();
        Put this line in if you want the armour to never be cursed. This
        should be used very sparingly. It will prevent the 1% chance that
        any given armour or armour in the game will be cursed.  It should
        be stressed that this should only be set on items that under no
        circumstances should be cursed. I.e. quest items etc.

set_value(-1, ##);
        Replace ## by an integer value to INCREASE the value of this armour
        above the default value. Use this instead of the normal call to
        set_value(-1); if you want your armour to be extra valuable.

set_dodge_bonus(bonus)
        Replace bonus with an integer value. The armour's dodge bonus
        increases the wielder's dodging stat (average of dex, wis) while
        using this armour. A negative value will reduce the wielder's
        dodging stat. This is a very powerful ability and should be used
        sparingly. (A 6 point increase is roughly equivalent to a level's
        increase in stats) armours with a dodge_bonus are considered
        exceptional or unique; see wizhelp 4.14 'uniques' for details.

set_arm_light(light);
        Replace light with an integer value. This setting allows you to
        make armour that gives off light. The parameter passed is how
        powerful the light is. 0 = none, 1 is normal day/sun light, and
        higher would mean very bright light. Setting this to a negative
        number would make the armour absorb that much light.

set_guild_allow(GUILD|GUILD|...);
        Replace GUILD|GUILD|... with an ORed set of guild defines (from
        guildd.h) which indicate which guilds are allowed to use this
        armour, armour restrictions notwithstanding. In order to use this
        setting, you must include guildd.h at the beginning of your file.

set_guild_restrict(GUILD|GUILD|...);
        This function is the same as set_guild_allow() except it will
        disallow the use of that particular armour by the guilds you have
        listed.

set_weakness(TYPE|TYPE|..., amount);
        Replace TYPE|TYPE|... with an ORed set of damage defines (from
        types.h) which indicate what damage types the wearer of this armour
        becomes extra weak to. Replace amount with the percentage increase
        in vulnerability to the given types.

set_resistance(TYPE|TYPE|..., amount);
        Replace TYPE|TYPE|... with an ORed set of damage defines (from
        types.h) which indicate what damage types the wearer of this armour
        becomes more resistant to. Replace amount with the percentage
        increase resistance to the given types.

***************************************************************************
                              Wear/Remove Functions
***************************************************************************
Wear/remove functions cause things to happen when the armour is worn or
removed. This is useful for example, if you want to give some spam when
the item is worn, or give some stat boosts to the player etc.

set_wear_func(oFuncObject);
        Pass the object that defines wear_func() and remove_func()
        (explained below) as oFuncObject. In most cases, oFuncObject
        this_object(). Whenever the armour is worn oFuncObject->
        wield_func(this_object()) will be called, and whenever removed,
        oFuncObject->remove_func(this_object()) will be called.

int wear_func(oArmour);
        This function is defined in the oFuncObject passed to
        set_wear_func(). Usually both functions are in the armour anyway.
        This function gets called if the set_wear_func() was set, and
        a player/monster tries to wear this armour. It is the builder's
        job to fill out the this function with whatever special things
        that are to happen. If this function returns 0, then the wear
        will fail. Thus you can use this to block a armour being worn
        by certain people.

int remove_func(oArmour);
        This function is defined in the oFuncObject passed to
        set_wear_func(). Usually both functions are in the armour anyway.
        This function gets called if the set_wear_func() was set, and
        a player/monster tries to remove this armour. It is the builder's
        job to fill out the this function with whatever special things
        that are to happen. If this function returns 0, then the remove
        will fail.

        Armour with a scripted wear effect must declare that effect for
        gearcheck with add_power_feature("scripted_wear", ...). See
        wizhelp 4.26 for the equipment power API and examples.

|CKBvoid add_equipment_stat(string sStat, int iValue, string sStart, string sSto
p);|XX0
        This function will handle adding the stat sStat to the
        player when they wear the item, and remove the stat when
        the player removes the item. It eliminates the need of
        creating start_wearing/stop_wearing functions in the item.
        sStat can be "con","dex","int","wis","str","chr","hp","sp",
      |RK0    "tmp_to_hit_stat","tmp_to_dam_stat","tmp_to_dodge_stat",|XX0
      |RK0    "tmp_to_absorb_stat","tmp_to_crit_stat","tmp_to_swings",|XX0
      |RK0    "tmp_to_hit","tmp_to_dam","tmp_to_dodge","tmp_to_absorb",|XX0
      |RK0    "tmp_to_crit","tmp_to_type"|XX0
      |RK0    tmp_to_* should only be used with permission.|XX0
        sStart is the message when the player wears the armor.
        sStop is the message when the player stops wearing the armor.
        The message is in the same format as room_message.
      |RK0  The messages should only be used once per item, not stat.|XX0
    |GKBExample:|XX0add_equipment_stat("con",5,"$N $vseem hardier.",
        "$N $vseem less robust.");

